<catsoop-section>What's Happening</catsoop-section>

Critical thinking is essential to achieve this goal efficiently. Although it's observed that the puzzle can be solved in at least **38 moves**, players can aim to minimize their own number of moves. Efforts are directed toward reducing the number of moves required with each attempt.

The puzzle's design necessitates a methodical approach, with only one cube able to be moved at a time and one empty space available. To achieve the desired configuration on the top face, each cube ideally needs to be flipped at least twice, requiring precise initial moves.

This puzzle demonstrates several computational concepts:

- **State space search** — Finding a path from initial state to goal state
- **Sliding puzzle mechanics** — Similar to the classic 15-puzzle
- **Optimization** — Minimizing the number of moves
- **Constraint satisfaction** — Only one cube can move at a time into the empty space

